{
  "text": "The epinephrine-induced rise in extracellular adenosine also may account, in part, for the low-plasma free fatty acid and glycerol levels seen on epinephrine infusion in these swine. The in vivo findings, which suggest low lipolytic sensitivity, contrast with in vitro findings in which adipocytes isolated from exercisetrained swine fed moderate amounts of feed have greater lipolytic sensitivity than adipocytes isolated from sedentary or overfed swine. This discrepancy between lipolysis in vitro and in vivo, noted by others [CITATION_1] , suggests the involvement of other physiological mechanisms present in intact adipose tissue that may regulate extracellular adenosine level. Such mechanisms may involve the rapid uptake of adenosine by endothelial cells, as observed in heart tissue [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , or an increase in epinephrine-stimulated blood flow, as observed with exercise training in humans [CITATION_4] .",
